{
  "terms": [
    {
      "term": "Generation",
      "simpleDefinition": "The process of producing electrical energy from various fuel sources or natural forces.",
      "anchor": "The 'start point' of the electrical supply chain where energy is created.",
      "misconception": "Thinking electricity is only generated in large power stations; it also includes small-scale micro-generation."
    },
    {
      "term": "Transmission Voltages",
      "simpleDefinition": "Extremely high voltage levels used to move electricity efficiently over long distances across the country.",
      "anchor": "The 'motorway' of the grid, specifically 132 kV, 275 kV, and 400 kV.",
      "misconception": "Confusing these high voltages with the lower 'distribution' voltages used to supply streets and houses."
    },
    {
      "term": "Micro-generation",
      "simpleDefinition": "Small-scale production of electricity by individual consumers, such as solar panels on a house.",
      "anchor": "Local power production that can feed back into the main grid.",
      "misconception": "Believing that all electricity in the network must come from a central national power station."
    },
    {
      "term": "Photovoltaic (PV)",
      "simpleDefinition": "A method of generating electricity by converting sunlight directly into electrical energy.",
      "anchor": "Solar panels found on domestic roofs or in large solar farms.",
      "misconception": "Thinking solar panels require heat to work; they actually generate power from light."
    },
    {
      "term": "Biomass",
      "simpleDefinition": "Generating electricity by burning organic materials like wood, plants, or processed waste.",
      "anchor": "Using biological matter as a fuel source instead of coal or gas.",
      "misconception": "Assuming biomass is a fossil fuel; it is actually a renewable energy source."
    },
    {
      "term": "kV (Kilovolt)",
      "simpleDefinition": "A unit of electrical pressure equal to 1,000 volts.",
      "anchor": "1 kV = 1,000 Volts.",
      "misconception": "Underestimating the scale of transmission by forgetting that 'k' represents a multiplier of one thousand."
    }
  ],
  "anchorPhrases": [
    "The three UK transmission voltages are 132 kV, 275 kV, and 400 kV.",
    "Generation methods range from fossil fuels like coal and gas to renewables like wind and wave.",
    "Transmission is the high-voltage transport of power before it is stepped down for distribution."
  ],
  "misconceptionTargets": [
    "Mixing up transmission voltages (132kV+) with distribution voltages (33kV or 11kV).",
    "Excluding micro-generation or renewables when identifying generation methods.",
    "Treating all high-voltage terms as interchangeable regardless of the specific kV value."
  ]
}

{
  "teachChecks": [
    {
      "title": "Generation Methods",
      "objective": "Identify the range of generation methods used for electricity distribution.",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "Electricity generation is the starting point of the supply chain. It is the process where various forms of energy are converted into electrical power. In the UK, we use a diverse mix of fuel sources and technologies to ensure a steady supply. This includes traditional fossil fuels like coal, oil, and gas, as well as nuclear power stations. We also rely on renewable energy sources that harness natural forces, such as wind, wave, and hydro (water) power.",
        "Beyond these large-scale methods, we use biomass, which involves burning organic materials, and photovoltaic (PV) systems, which convert sunlight directly into electricity. A key concept to understand is micro-generation. This refers to small-scale production, such as solar panels on a domestic roof or a small wind turbine. Unlike massive power stations, micro-generation allows individual buildings to produce their own power and feed the excess back into the distribution network. As an electrician, you must recognize all ten of these methods—coal, oil, gas, nuclear, wind, wave, hydro, biomass, photovoltaic, and micro-generation—as the primary sources feeding the grid."
      ],
      "hint": "Remember to include both large-scale fossil fuels and small-scale sources like micro-generation."
    },
    {
      "title": "Transmission Voltages",
      "objective": "Identify the specific voltage levels used for the transmission of electricity.",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "Once electricity is generated, it must be transported across the country to reach towns and cities. This process is called transmission. To move electricity efficiently over long distances and minimize energy loss, we use extremely high voltages. Think of the transmission network as the 'motorway' of the electrical grid, designed for high-speed, high-capacity transport before the power reaches local streets.",
        "In the UK, there are three specific transmission voltages you must identify: 400 kV, 275 kV, and 132 kV. The unit 'kV' stands for kilovolt, where 1 kV equals 1,000 volts. Therefore, 400 kV is a massive 400,000 volts. These voltages are typically carried by large steel pylons and heavy-duty overhead lines. It is a common mistake to confuse these with lower 'distribution' voltages, such as 33 kV or 11 kV. Transmission is strictly reserved for these three highest levels (132 kV and above). Distinguishing between transmission and distribution is critical for understanding the hierarchy of the National Grid and ensuring safety when identifying network components."
      ],
      "hint": "Focus on the three highest values: 132 kV, 275 kV, and 400 kV."
    }
  ]
}

